the reality of over 10 million children living in the streets of the island nation. The Land of the Hibiscus is home to some of the poorest people on the planet. Workers of the ministry have seen unbelievable pictures of the crowded garbage dumps in the nation. Children can be found rummaging and searching through trash for food in these landfills.

All of this happened in 2008, while the Caribbean earthquake struck in January and the aftermath of it is still felt today. A very large percentage of those who lost their lives were in the poorest section of the country. When this disaster occurred, We Are Gods Hands started a rebuilding project to aid the people. Not just helping to physically rebuild, but to put Christ back in their lives.

We Were No Stranger to the People of Haiti

We Are Gods Hands has a strong relationship with the pastors and churches in Haiti, but that partnership dates all the way back to 1961, when Pattie and Ritchie Bowden served as missionaries in an orphanage and school, teaching children about Jesus Christ.

When the source of ministry first ventured into Haiti, there was a plague of sickness and death that caused hundreds of children to have no hope left, due to the lengthy time of starvation. One extremely hungry child wandered into Ritchies workshop one day and beat on the door until he let him inside and had compassion on him. This poor cruelty-stricken child was fed and embraced by the Bowdens and was Christianized at the same time.
